interpretation: Stoop or step as part of construction built into the doorway, possibly in association with the narrowing of the door, as the step fits the width of the final doorway. Tiles lain flat below the rock construction as part of an obvious leveling action, probably associated with the contruction of 657, which had packing of stones-Does not seem to be covered by 519. Follows width of narrowed door, but probably built at or durring time of 519's deposition
Given the nature of the ceramic evidence for the associated layer, it may in fact be more likely that this structure was associated with the upper elevations of the walls of the bedrock-cut structure
cxt.observations: Packing fill beneath wall contruction removed as same context. No stratigraphic breaks between stones and bedrock.
cxt.description: Stone construction in doorway, a stoop/step. Three stones across laid in a discrete orientation, laid flat on tiles in obvious leveling action.
Terreno molto fine e polveroso forse in parte di origine eolica, ma apparentemente con una buona quantita di cenere. Forse anteriore al crollo (US72), ma non e possibile stabilirlo.

cxt.description: Tile and articulated vessels in the bottom layer of collapse in the southeast area of room 32.  Tile fall of sr341 located above sr356.  Concentration of carbonized wood mostly under tile and mixed with soil.
cxt.definition: Tile/articulated vessels/bottom layer of collapse in southeast part of room 32

cxt.interpretation: The collapse of the walls of the room
cxt.observations: Tile not counted. Presence of ceramics (not a lot) and later metal goods. Glazed ceramics present in the SW corner; [in the same corner,] remains of a wooden object with vertical direction of lines in it (bad preservation).
cxt.description: Includes stones of different sizes; ceramic fragments (with different dating - mostly Byz[antine]); frags of glass goods; iron slag frags (iron nails, other metal goods). The quantity of the soil in the upper horizons is less than the lower, colour from dark gray to gray.

cxt.interpretation: Collapse of southern and eastern walls of the room
cxt.dating elements: frag of pottery present 11th to 13th Century
cxt.observations: SR392 e 393 are probably from the same moment of the collapse, since ther isn't a clear boundary between them.
cxt.description: Medium stones in a loose sandy brown soil with roots and frags of plaster. Near the closed doorway (wall N-E )there is some traces of charcoal. towards the centre of the layer color changes to yellowish brown.
cxt.definition: Layer of collapse in N  corner of room 33.
